description: From Canadian French tamarac, believed to derive from an Algonquian word.
In the 19th century, some authorities questioned if tacamahac, tamarack, and hackmatack could be cognate to one another, perhaps all corruptions of one term, but such cognacy is unlikely.

entries.meaning: Any of several North American larches, of the genus Larix.
examples: The women peeled tamarack bark for tea, dug through the deep snow in hopes of finding a few dried fiddleheads.

entries.meaning: The wood from such a tree.
